{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":500,"text":"The global economic financial crisis has reignited public interest"},{"time":5000,"text":"in something that's actually one of the oldest questions in economics,"},{"time":8416,"text":"dating back to at least before Adam Smith."},{"time":11100,"text":"And that is, why is it that countries with seemingly similar economies and institutions"},{"time":16584,"text":"can display radically different savings behavior?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":19833,"text":"Now, many brilliant economists have spent their entire lives working on this question,"},{"time":24367,"text":"and as a field we've made a tremendous amount of headway"},{"time":27784,"text":"and we understand a lot about this."},{"time":30217,"text":"What I'm here to talk with you about today is an intriguing new hypothesis"},{"time":33851,"text":"and some surprisingly powerful new findings that I've been working on"},{"time":37883,"text":"about the link between the structure of the language you speak"},{"time":42604,"text":"and how you find yourself with the propensity to save."},{"time":47000,"text":"Let me tell you a little bit about savings rates, a little bit about language,"},{"time":50067,"text":"and then I'll draw that connection."}]},{"cues":[{"time":52417,"text":"Let's start by thinking about the member countries of the OECD,"},{"time":56984,"text":"or the Organization of Economic Cooperation and Development."},{"time":60285,"text":"OECD countries, by and large, you should think about these"},{"time":64184,"text":"as the richest, most industrialized countries in the world."},{"time":66822,"text":"And by joining the OECD, they were affirming a common commitment"},{"time":70872,"text":"to democracy, open markets and free trade."},{"time":74310,"text":"Despite all of these similarities, we see huge differences in savings behavior."}]},{"cues":[{"time":78995,"text":"So all the way over on the left of this graph,"},{"time":81445,"text":"what you see is many OECD countries saving over a quarter of their GDP every year,"},{"time":86179,"text":"and some OECD countries saving over a third of their GDP per year."},{"time":90860,"text":"Holding down the right flank of the OECD, all the way on the other side, is Greece."},{"time":95628,"text":"And what you can see is that over the last 25 years,"},{"time":99044,"text":"Greece has barely managed to save more than 10 percent of their GDP."},{"time":102944,"text":"It should be noted, of course, that the United States and the U.K. are the next in line."}]},{"cues":[{"time":109818,"text":"Now that we see these huge differences in savings rates,"},{"time":112396,"text":"how is it possible that language might have something to do with these differences?"},{"time":116062,"text":"Let me tell you a little bit about how languages fundamentally differ."},{"time":119111,"text":"Linguists and cognitive scientists have been exploring this question for many years now."},{"time":124678,"text":"And then I'll draw the connection between these two behaviors."}]},{"cues":[{"time":129288,"text":"Many of you have probably already noticed that I'm Chinese."},{"time":131896,"text":"I grew up in the Midwest of the United States."},{"time":134861,"text":"And something I realized quite early on"},{"time":137312,"text":"was that the Chinese language forced me to speak about and --"},{"time":140903,"text":"in fact, more fundamentally than that --"},{"time":143794,"text":"ever so slightly forced me to think about family in very different ways."}]},{"cues":[{"time":147884,"text":"Now, how might that be? Let me give you an example."},{"time":149961,"text":"Suppose I were talking with you and I was introducing you to my uncle."},{"time":154363,"text":"You understood exactly what I just said in English."},{"time":157229,"text":"If we were speaking Mandarin Chinese with each other, though,"},{"time":160179,"text":"I wouldn't have that luxury."},{"time":162245,"text":"I wouldn't have been able to convey so little information."},{"time":165078,"text":"What my language would have forced me to do,"},{"time":167462,"text":"instead of just telling you, \"This is my uncle,\""},{"time":169462,"text":"is to tell you a tremendous amount of additional information."},{"time":172744,"text":"My language would force me to tell you"},{"time":174563,"text":"whether or not this was an uncle on my mother's side or my father's side,"},{"time":177979,"text":"whether this was an uncle by marriage or by birth,"},{"time":181063,"text":"and if this man was my father's brother,"},{"time":183295,"text":"whether he was older than or younger than my father."},{"time":186079,"text":"All of this information is obligatory. Chinese doesn't let me ignore it."},{"time":190212,"text":"And in fact, if I want to speak correctly,"},{"time":192378,"text":"Chinese forces me to constantly think about it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":195495,"text":"Now, that fascinated me endlessly as a child,"},{"time":199444,"text":"but what fascinates me even more today as an economist"},{"time":202679,"text":"is that some of these same differences carry through to how languages speak about time."},{"time":207980,"text":"So for example, if I'm speaking in English, I have to speak grammatically differently"},{"time":212229,"text":"if I'm talking about past rain, \"It rained yesterday,\""},{"time":214962,"text":"current rain, \"It is raining now,\""},{"time":217194,"text":"or future rain, \"It will rain tomorrow.\""},{"time":219628,"text":"Notice that English requires a lot more information with respect to the timing of events."},{"time":224455,"text":"Why? Because I have to consider that"},{"time":226462,"text":"and I have to modify what I'm saying to say, \"It will rain,\" or \"It's going to rain.\""},{"time":231245,"text":"It's simply not permissible in English to say, \"It rain tomorrow.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":235361,"text":"In contrast to that, that's almost exactly what you would say in Chinese."},{"time":239545,"text":"A Chinese speaker can basically say something"},{"time":241861,"text":"that sounds very strange to an English speaker's ears."},{"time":244445,"text":"They can say, \"Yesterday it rain,\" \"Now it rain,\" \"Tomorrow it rain.\""},{"time":249012,"text":"In some deep sense, Chinese doesn't divide up the time spectrum"},{"time":252875,"text":"in the same way that English forces us to constantly do in order to speak correctly."}]},{"cues":[{"time":259308,"text":"Is this difference in languages"},{"time":260892,"text":"only between very, very distantly related languages, like English and Chinese?"},{"time":265087,"text":"Actually, no."},{"time":266045,"text":"So many of you know, in this room, that English is a Germanic language."},{"time":269778,"text":"What you may not have realized is that English is actually an outlier."},{"time":273693,"text":"It is the only Germanic language that requires this."},{"time":276943,"text":"For example, most other Germanic language speakers"},{"time":279827,"text":"feel completely comfortable talking about rain tomorrow"},{"time":282844,"text":"by saying, \"Morgen regnet es,\""},{"time":284810,"text":"quite literally to an English ear, \"It rain tomorrow.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":288710,"text":"This led me, as a behavioral economist, to an intriguing hypothesis."},{"time":293777,"text":"Could how you speak about time, could how your language forces you to think about time,"},{"time":298026,"text":"affect your propensity to behave across time?"},{"time":301777,"text":"You speak English, a futured language."},{"time":304677,"text":"And what that means is that every time you discuss the future,"},{"time":307844,"text":"or any kind of a future event,"},{"time":309411,"text":"grammatically you're forced to cleave that from the present"},{"time":312810,"text":"and treat it as if it's something viscerally different."},{"time":315443,"text":"Now suppose that that visceral difference"},{"time":317943,"text":"makes you subtly dissociate the future from the present every time you speak."},{"time":322143,"text":"If that's true and it makes the future feel"},{"time":324056,"text":"like something more distant and more different from the present,"},{"time":327039,"text":"that's going to make it harder to save."},{"time":329693,"text":"If, on the other hand, you speak a futureless language,"},{"time":332244,"text":"the present and the future, you speak about them identically."},{"time":335627,"text":"If that subtly nudges you to feel about them identically,"},{"time":338610,"text":"that's going to make it easier to save."}]},{"cues":[{"time":340994,"text":"Now this is a fanciful theory."},{"time":343544,"text":"I'm a professor, I get paid to have fanciful theories."},{"time":346444,"text":"But how would you actually go about testing such a theory?"},{"time":350678,"text":"Well, what I did with that was to access the linguistics literature."},{"time":354744,"text":"And interestingly enough, there are pockets of futureless language speakers"},{"time":359127,"text":"situated all over the world."},{"time":361060,"text":"This is a pocket of futureless language speakers in Northern Europe."},{"time":364426,"text":"Interestingly enough, when you start to crank the data,"},{"time":367327,"text":"these pockets of futureless language speakers all around the world"},{"time":370560,"text":"turn out to be, by and large, some of the world's best savers."}]},{"cues":[{"time":374494,"text":"Just to give you a hint of that,"},{"time":376660,"text":"let's look back at that OECD graph that we were talking about."},{"time":379410,"text":"What you see is that these bars are systematically taller"},{"time":382794,"text":"and systematically shifted to the left"},{"time":384926,"text":"compared to these bars which are the members of the OECD that speak futured languages."},{"time":389444,"text":"What is the average difference here?"},{"time":390907,"text":"Five percentage points of your GDP saved per year."},{"time":394193,"text":"Over 25 years that has huge long-run effects on the wealth of your nation."}]},{"cues":[{"time":398927,"text":"Now while these findings are suggestive,"},{"time":401627,"text":"countries can be different in so many different ways"},{"time":403693,"text":"that it's very, very difficult sometimes to account for all of these possible differences."},{"time":408077,"text":"What I'm going to show you, though, is something that I've been engaging in for a year,"},{"time":412109,"text":"which is trying to gather all of the largest datasets"},{"time":414432,"text":"that we have access to as economists,"},{"time":416724,"text":"and I'm going to try and strip away all of those possible differences,"},{"time":420106,"text":"hoping to get this relationship to break."},{"time":422760,"text":"And just in summary, no matter how far I push this, I can't get it to break."},{"time":427791,"text":"Let me show you how far you can do that."}]},{"cues":[{"time":429556,"text":"One way to imagine that is I gather large datasets from around the world."},{"time":434189,"text":"So for example, there is the Survey of Health, [Aging] and Retirement in Europe."},{"time":437923,"text":"From this dataset you actually learn that retired European families"},{"time":441757,"text":"are extremely patient with survey takers."},{"time":444390,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":446306,"text":"So imagine that you're a retired household in Belgium and someone comes to your front door."},{"time":450690,"text":"\"Excuse me, would you mind if I peruse your stock portfolio?"},{"time":455274,"text":"Do you happen to know how much your house is worth? Do you mind telling me?"},{"time":458806,"text":"Would you happen to have a hallway that's more than 10 meters long?"},{"time":462073,"text":"If you do, would you mind if I timed how long it took you to walk down that hallway?"},{"time":466574,"text":"Would you mind squeezing as hard as you can, in your dominant hand, this device"},{"time":470471,"text":"so I can measure your grip strength?"},{"time":471983,"text":"How about blowing into this tube so I can measure your lung capacity?\""},{"time":476006,"text":"The survey takes over a day."},{"time":478890,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":480373,"text":"Combine that with a Demographic and Health Survey"},{"time":484273,"text":"collected by USAID in developing countries in Africa, for example,"},{"time":488723,"text":"which that survey actually can go so far as to directly measure the HIV status"},{"time":493874,"text":"of families living in, for example, rural Nigeria."},{"time":496973,"text":"Combine that with a world value survey,"},{"time":498874,"text":"which measures the political opinions and, fortunately for me, the savings behaviors"},{"time":503307,"text":"of millions of families in hundreds of countries around the world."}]},{"cues":[{"time":508006,"text":"Take all of that data, combine it, and this map is what you get."},{"time":511824,"text":"What you find is nine countries around the world"},{"time":514074,"text":"that have significant native populations"},{"time":516726,"text":"which speak both futureless and futured languages."},{"time":520773,"text":"And what I'm going to do is form statistical matched pairs"},{"time":524307,"text":"between families that are nearly identical on every dimension that I can measure,"},{"time":529900,"text":"and then I'm going to explore whether or not the link between language and savings holds"},{"time":533437,"text":"even after controlling for all of these levels."}]},{"cues":[{"time":536920,"text":"What are the characteristics we can control for?"},{"time":539137,"text":"Well I'm going to match families on country of birth and residence,"},{"time":541901,"text":"the demographics -- what sex, their age --"},{"time":544303,"text":"their income level within their own country,"},{"time":546437,"text":"their educational achievement, a lot about their family structure."},{"time":549452,"text":"It turns out there are six different ways to be married in Europe."},{"time":552970,"text":"And most granularly, I break them down by religion"},{"time":557170,"text":"where there are 72 categories of religions in the world --"},{"time":560485,"text":"so an extreme level of granularity."},{"time":562202,"text":"There are 1.4 billion different ways that a family can find itself."}]},{"cues":[{"time":566735,"text":"Now effectively everything I'm going to tell you from now on"},{"time":570784,"text":"is only comparing these basically nearly identical families."},{"time":573834,"text":"It's getting as close as possible to the thought experiment"},{"time":576334,"text":"of finding two families both of whom live in Brussels"},{"time":579267,"text":"who are identical on every single one of these dimensions,"},{"time":582267,"text":"but one of whom speaks Flemish and one of whom speaks French;"},{"time":585383,"text":"or two families that live in a rural district in Nigeria,"},{"time":588100,"text":"one of whom speaks Hausa and one of whom speaks Igbo."}]},{"cues":[{"time":591933,"text":"Now even after all of this granular level of control,"},{"time":595817,"text":"do futureless language speakers seem to save more?"},{"time":598983,"text":"Yes, futureless language speakers, even after this level of control,"},{"time":602636,"text":"are 30 percent more likely to report having saved in any given year."},{"time":606334,"text":"Does this have cumulative effects?"},{"time":608150,"text":"Yes, by the time they retire, futureless language speakers, holding constant their income,"},{"time":612570,"text":"are going to retire with 25 percent more in savings."}]},{"cues":[{"time":615638,"text":"Can we push this data even further?"},{"time":618119,"text":"Yes, because I just told you, we actually collect a lot of health data as economists."},{"time":623418,"text":"Now how can we think about health behaviors to think about savings?"},{"time":627301,"text":"Well, think about smoking, for example."},{"time":630134,"text":"Smoking is in some deep sense negative savings."},{"time":633317,"text":"If savings is current pain in exchange for future pleasure,"},{"time":636983,"text":"smoking is just the opposite."},{"time":638291,"text":"It's current pleasure in exchange for future pain."},{"time":641150,"text":"What we should expect then is the opposite effect."},{"time":644100,"text":"And that's exactly what we find."},{"time":645868,"text":"Futureless language speakers are 20 to 24 percent less likely"},{"time":649635,"text":"to be smoking at any given point in time compared to identical families,"},{"time":653050,"text":"and they're going to be 13 to 17 percent less likely"},{"time":655951,"text":"to be obese by the time they retire,"},{"time":658168,"text":"and they're going to report being 21 percent more likely"},{"time":660631,"text":"to have used a condom in their last sexual encounter."},{"time":662918,"text":"I could go on and on with the list of differences that you can find."},{"time":666401,"text":"It's almost impossible not to find a savings behavior"},{"time":670201,"text":"for which this strong effect isn't present."}]},{"cues":[{"time":672800,"text":"My linguistics and economics colleagues at Yale and I are just starting to do this work"},{"time":677550,"text":"and really explore and understand the ways that these subtle nudges"},{"time":682717,"text":"cause us to think more or less about the future every single time we speak."},{"time":688112,"text":"Ultimately, the goal,"},{"time":690413,"text":"once we understand how these subtle effects can change our decision making,"},{"time":694612,"text":"we want to be able to provide people tools"},{"time":697562,"text":"so that they can consciously make themselves better savers"},{"time":700370,"text":"and more conscious investors in their own future."}]},{"cues":[{"time":703629,"text":"Thank you very much."}]},{"cues":[{"time":705896,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}